{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564279"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:11:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:11:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16962"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16962"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.05,0.12,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110606"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9652"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16962"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4043"},{"type":"tags","id":"4689"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110606"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of urinary incontinence. She describes sudden, intense urges to void followed by involuntary leakage of urine. These episodes occur multiple times per day and are significantly affecting her quality of life. She has tried reducing caffeine intake and performing pelvic floor exercises without improvement. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has had three vaginal deliveries, the last one eight years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Pelvic examination reveals normal external genitalia with no evidence of prolapse or stress incontinence on coughing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluoxetine","Duloxetine","Tension-free vaginal tape","Insertion of a ring pessary","Oxybutynin hydrochloride"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of urge incontinence (overactive bladder), characterised by sudden, intense urges to void followed by involuntary leakage. She has already attempted conservative measures including lifestyle modifications and pelvic floor exercises without success, making pharmacological therapy appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxybutynin hydrochloride\u003C/strong\u003E is an antimuscarinic medication that reduces bladder contractions and is the first-line pharmacological treatment for urge incontinence. It works by blocking acetylcholine receptors in the bladder, reducing detrusor muscle overactivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuloxetine\u003C/strong\u003E is a serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor primarily used for stress incontinence as it increases urethral sphincter tone. It would not be appropriate for urge incontinence where the problem is detrusor muscle overactivity rather than sphincter weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor that has no role in the management of urge incontinence. While it may be used for depression or anxiety, it does not address the underlying bladder dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension-free vaginal tape\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure used for stress incontinence. It would not help with urge incontinence as it does not address the underlying problem of detrusor overactivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of a ring pessary\u003C/strong\u003E is used for pelvic organ prolapse and would not help with urge incontinence symptoms. This patient has no evidence of prolapse on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of urge incontinence follows a stepwise approach, starting with lifestyle modifications and bladder training, followed by pharmacological therapy with antimuscarinics, and only proceeding to more invasive options if these measures fail.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line management of urge incontinence includes lifestyle modifications and bladder training.","Antimuscarinic medications like oxybutynin are the first-line pharmacological treatment for urge incontinence.","Urge incontinence is characterised by sudden, intense urges to void with involuntary leakage."],"references":["Nandy S, Ranganathan S. Urge Incontinence. [Updated 2022 Sep 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563172/","Hutchinson A, Nesbitt A, Joshi A, Clubb A, Perera M. Overactive bladder syndrome [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020: 49 (9). Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/september/overactive-bladder-syndrome"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16962"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92851","links